                                                                              "grok_mode":  "Normal",
                                                                              "message":  "The Russian Federation began to significantly restrict the activities of NGOs through various legislative measures:\n\n- **2012**: The \"Foreign Agents\" law was introduced, requiring NGOs that receive foreign funding and engage in what the Russian government labels as \"political activity\" to register as \"foreign agents\", a term with negative connotations in Russian.\n\n- **May 2015**: President Vladimir Putin signed a law allowing Russian authorities to ban foreign NGOs deemed \"undesirable\" from operating inside Russia. This law allows the prosecutor general to designate any foreign or international NGO as \"undesirable\" if it\u0027s perceived to threaten \"the foundations of the constitutional system of the Russian Federation, the defense capability of the country, or the security of the state.\" \n\n- **July 2015**: The National Endowment for Democracy became the first organization officially blacklisted under this \"undesirable organizations\" law.\n\n- **2023**: Further legislation was introduced to prohibit collaboration with unregistered foreign NGOs, severely limiting civic space by making participation in their activities an administrative offense with fines.\n\n- **2024**: There were amendments to the law, expanding the scope of what could be considered an \"undesirable organization\", making cooperation with such entities a criminal offense.\n\nTherefore, while NGOs were not outright \"banned\" in one fell swoop, the legislative measures taken since 2012, particularly the 2015 law on \"undesirable organizations\", have progressively tightened the operational space for NGOs, especially those with foreign affiliations or funding, in Russia.",
